# Keep IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md Updated

When you make a change that alters the architecture of the project — not just feature behavior — update `IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md` in the same response.

## What triggers an update

- Adding, removing, or renaming a Redux slice
- Changing the data strategy for a slice (e.g., switching from one-time load to real-time subscription)
- Adding or removing a route in `App.tsx`
- Adding or removing a backend API endpoint
- Adding a new major dependency that changes how something works at an architectural level
- Adding or removing a service in the backend (`services/`)
- Meaningful changes to the shared types that affect how the layers interact
- Changing whether data is persisted, optimistic, or real-time

## What does NOT trigger an update

- Adding a new feature within an existing slice and existing routes
- Adding new components under existing features
- CSS and styling changes
- Bug fixes
- Refactors that don't change the architectural shape

## How to update IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md

- Edit only the relevant section(s). Do not rewrite the whole file.
- Keep descriptions high-level. Do not paste code or go into function-level detail — the code is the source of truth at that level.
- Do not add user-facing feature descriptions here — those belong in `SPEC.md`.
- Do not record design alternatives that were rejected, or rationale for decisions that are now settled.
- See `documentation.mdc` for the full doc ownership and no-duplication policy.
